content.description: Climb up a left dihedral. The crux is halfway up. Don't let the corner pull you in, stem out.
content.protection: Traditional, it takes small gear and thins near the top. Save a #2 for the last move.
content.location:
This route is just left of

Early Start

.

content.description:
This is a really excellent route - with thin, balancy, well-bolted climbing! It’s probably one of the best routes at the crag.

I don’t know the FA information, please contact me if you know it. Thank you to whoever put it up!
content.location:
It is the first route to the right of

Juniper Corner

.

content.description: This is another great route with quite a few fun and challenging moves. There are some big high steps. The crux seemed to be passing the first bolt, but the bolt placement is good. I don’t know the FA information, please contact me if you know it. Thank you to whoever put it up!
content.location:
It is second route to the right of

Juniper Corner

.

content.description: Tongue Thaied ascends good quality rock. It thins near the top.
content.location:
Walk past

Binky of the Mountains

to two open face slabs with 4 sport routes.

content.description: Work your way up to the big ledge. Then climb through a left leaning seam on the big flake at the beginning. Move up on somewhat crimpy climbing for 5.8, swinging right and using a hole.
content.location:
This is just right of

Guido's Face

and just left of Plumber's Crack.

content.description: Climb up the right side of the left-leaning pinnacle with some somewhat thin face moves.
content.location:
This is on the right side of a left-leaning, west-facing pinnacle about 50' west of the Main Wall and

El Gecko

.

content.description:
This is a fun, little, mixed climb that would see more ascents if it wasn't so runout at the top.

Start in a thin hands/finger crack with decent gear, then move up onto the main face. Clip the first bolt, then make thin moves up past a second bolt (crux). The climbing lets up a little here, but it's a long ways to the chains with no decent gear.
content.protection: Small cams and/or nuts for the crack down low, plus two quickdraws, 1 bolt, and 1 piton rap anchor.
content.location:
Scot-Free is located about 200' west of where the main approach trail meets the Upper Tier.

Continue walking west from

Simpatico

and

Border Patrol

, and about 100 feet away, you'll find a large corner. Scot-Free is the face climb on the arete, next to a dirty chimney with a large chockstone up high.

content.description: The crux is at the first bolt.  It is a great climb.
content.protection: 6 bolts and an anchor with chains at the top.
content.location: The route is right in front of you when the main trail meets the wall.

content.description:
Juniper Corner ascends a right-facing corner with a tight hands start that thins to fingers and tips. The crux is the thin part near the top.

Anyone with the FA info and actual route name, let me know in the comments.
content.location:
Walk a good ways left from the approach trail. This right-facing corner is left of 2 bolted routes just past "

Ecstasy

" and "

Corner

."

content.description:
If anyone has any info on the route name or FA, let me know. There's not much info on MP for this area, so I figured I'd post it up.

This is a classic for the area. Climb an awesome hand crack in an open book, right-facing dihedral. The start is a roof with a wide crack (#5 Camalot, crux). Just above the roof, the crack narrows to a nice ~5.7 hand crack and then eases up a bit for a cruise to the anchors.
content.protection: You can sew it up with doubles from #1 to #3, and a #5 for the wide start. There is a bolted anchor.
content.location: The Green Wall is on the far left side of the upper tier. The splitter hand crack is on the right side of the green face.

content.description: Get up on the ledge where the route starts. Climb up a flake and then left on the face. The route is short, but fun somewhat crimpy climbing for 5.8.

Golden Rule is a 6 bolt line on quality stone through a roof - one of the steepest at upper tier. Use same start of

Black Streak

, and veer right to large horizontal break after C2 (an extended draw is helpful here). Hang on till you make tricky move right past C4, and balance your way up to hidden hold through final overlap before the anchor.
content.location:
It is just before

Black Streak

at an obvious overhang with plaque at its base.

content.description: The crux is right on the first bolt.  It is a great climb.
content.location:
The route is to the left of

Osso Bocco

, both of which are in front of you when the main hiker trail meets the wall.

content.description:
This is the route to the right of Plumber's Crack on the arete.  It is just to the right of where the main approach trail reaches the rock.

Consistent climbing up the arete or left face up a nice ramp.  Stemming to the left easing things.  Two bolts are on the right side of the arete and kind of easy to miss.
The crux is the last few moves of the climb.  This has pretty fun climbing up a dihedral with some good finger cracks.
content.protection: Small TCUs, some nuts, and a couple bigger cams should do the trick.
content.location: Where the main hiker's trail meets the wall, walk about 60 feet to your right.

content.description:
Immediately right of a nice corner crack and left of

Black Streak

is a 4 bolt climb with fun movement. The first bolt is reachy - either approach from crack (use gear or spotter) to make this clip or use a stick clip if you have any doubts. The direct start is a boulder problem on small edges. It is slightly runout after C4 to anchors on easy terrain.
content.protection: 4 clips to anchors that can be used for this route and 5.7 hand/layback crack on left.
content.location:
This is on the western side of the upper tier, past overhanging the

Golden Rule

and

Black Streak

.

climbs.name: The Curious Case of Benjamin Carson

content.description:
Climb the slightly overhanging face on positive edges past two bolts (stay out of the corner for full value!) before getting a good shake at a no-hands rest below the roof.

Be sure to head right out of the roof instead of getting sucked towards the choss on the left. Get a good gaston with your right hand, and make a big move to a hero jug. Pull up onto the ledge (a second no-hands rest) before finishing with some pocketed face climbing to the chains.
content.protection:
7 bolts to chains at the top.

Use a long draw on the last bolt below the roof

to reduce rope drag.
content.location:
On the far right side of the Upper Tier, 30 feet to the right of

Chupacabra

, this starts 5 feet to the left of a big, left-facing corner, below a 4 foot roof 30 feet up. The route is easily identifiable by its brown-painted bolts.

content.description: Crimpt-o-currency is a fun route! Reaching the hueco starts the route, I recommend carefully clipping the second bolt from the the hueco. The bolts protect crux moves nicely. You don’t really have to do any hard moves above bolts. Give it a try!
content.protection: 5 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor with rings.

content.description: The whole route is good!
content.location:
It shares chains with

Ecstacy

.

content.description: Start off a nice large belay ledge to the first bolt on top of a one-foot roof. Face climb to a mantle move on the corner. Easy moves lead to a nice upper face.
content.location: About 75 ft right of where the trail meets the rock. The bolts are 6 ft right of a nice dihedral.

content.description: CC is a fun, easy climb with great protection.
content.location:
This is West of

Border Patrol

. At the start, there is a big limb you can sit on.

content.description: Climb up a left-facing, left-leaning, overhanging dihedral and over a small roof.
content.location:
This is on a small, left-leaning, west-facing pinnacle, about 50' west from the Main Wall and

El Gecko

.

content.description: This is a tricky romp following a black water streak with a hard start right off the ground.
content.location:
It is between

Ecstasy

and

Golden Rule

.

content.description:
This is a short climb dedicated to a friend lost in 2009, Mikey Brown - aka Binky of the Mountains.

It is short and sweet with several fun variations. The route is just past an easy 5.6 just to the right called CC (also with a plaque at base) that is a good introductory kid's/beginner's climb for the area.
content.location: Once you top out on the trail under Osso Bocco, walk west until you see the route. You can't miss dead tree limbs hanging over the top left side of the route. The crux moves are after C4 - use your feet!

content.description: The crux is after the first bolt.
content.protection: 4 bolts and an anchor with rap rings.
content.location:
This is a sport route left of

Tongue Thaied

.
